Roles & Responsibilities
Overview
The Mobility Management is a new research project introduced in SMART FM Phase 2, which combines behavioural science, emerging transportation technology, and data anlaytics to develop a future urban mobility system for Singapore that integrates public transit, walking and bicycling, shared mobility and autonomous vehicles.  Current phase of the project focuses on demand preference formation and shaping, integrated transit system design, physiological emotional reactions, and social mobility sharing. The project is led by Prof. Jinhua Zhao at MIT. Please see https://mobility.mit.edu/  for his general research interest.
Responsibilities
We are seeking a Postdoctoral Associate who will be involved in the behavior mobility management project. The project consists of the following topics: 1) Preference Formation for Autonomous Vehicles; 2) Municipal Level Policy Agenda on New Mobility Service; 3) Autonomous Vehicles-Public Transit System Integration; and 4) Social Mobility Sharing: Dockless Bike and Ridesharing.
The specific job scope includes:
Develop stated preference surveys focusing on people’s attitude towards new transportation technologies, e.g. on-demand shared mobility service, autonomous vehicles;
Implement advanced behavioral or econometric modeling methods to study the formation and shaping of preference towards the new transportation technologies;
Use simulation or econometric methods to design and to evaluate new public transit systems integrating emerging transportation technologies based on current data from the real world;
Develop a full understanding of the interplay among travel behaviors and preference shaping, transport system design and policy, and emerging transportation technologies;
Work with team members from SMART and from MIT, regularly report with PIs and publish new findings in journals and/or conferences.
Supervise doctoral and master students.

